# Resume mode (implies --sync): every 'zfs receive' runs with -s, so an
# interrupted transfer leaves a resume token on the destination dataset.
# To continue, just run this same command again -- it detects the token
# and emits 'zfs send -t <token>' to finish the interrupted stream.
# A resumed run only finishes that stream; run the command once more
# afterwards to send any snapshots created since (sync incremental).
# To resume a single dataset by hand, read the token and feed it back:
#   zfs get -H -o value receive_resume_token <dest-dataset>
#   zfs send -t <token> | mbuffer -m 1G | zfs receive -s -u <dest-dataset>
# To discard a stale token instead: zfs receive -A <dest-dataset>
# tank/data - up to date
# skipping tank/data/b - no snapshots
# tank/data/c - no common snapshot, full send
# tank/data/d - resuming interrupted transfer from saved token
# tank/data/e - up to date
Error: tank/data/f@s1 - same name but different guid (guid/f@s1 vs guid-DIVERGED). Datasets are not related.
